The White House is expected today toname Thomas Griscom, a longtime aide to chief of staff HowardBaker, as President Reagan's communications director.    Officials said an announcement was expected to be madeduring Reagan's trip to Philadelphia where the president is tomake a speech to a group of doctors on the deadly disease AIDS(Acquired Immune Deficiency Syndrome).    Griscom, 37, was brought into the White House by formerSenator Baker to help with the transition after Baker was namedchief of staff following the resignation of Donald Regan in thewake of the Iran arms scandal.    He will take the job vacated by Patrick Buchanan, ahigh-profile conservative, who served two years ascommunications director. Reuter&#3;